WEBVTT

00:05.375 --> 00:07.175
Aren't you nervous to find out
what you got

00:07.210 --> 00:08.409
on the history midterm?

00:08.445 --> 00:10.445
[ Chuckles ]
I'm nervous about the time

00:10.480 --> 00:12.780
that Cap'n Crunch box turned me on.

00:12.816 --> 00:16.050
I <i> know </i> I aced the midterm.

00:16.085 --> 00:18.086
I got a smiley.

00:20.724 --> 00:22.490
Ah, there she is.

00:22.525 --> 00:23.825
Gather 'round, boys.

00:23.860 --> 00:28.263
You're about to see
my 4.0 face.

00:28.298 --> 00:30.999
[ Breathing rapidly ]

00:31.034 --> 00:36.104
Are...you...okay...
Steve?

00:36.139 --> 00:40.908
You...don't...look...
so...hot.

00:40.944 --> 00:43.011
Why are you talking like that?

00:43.046 --> 00:46.381
Too...much...Zoloft.

00:46.416 --> 00:49.817
And I'm still
so...sad.

00:49.853 --> 00:53.788
M-Mr. Herschel, I-I think
there's been a mistake.

00:53.823 --> 00:55.990
You put an "F" here on my test

00:56.026 --> 00:59.160
but forgot to add
"antastic job, A-plus."

00:59.195 --> 01:01.429
I was just as surprised
as you, Steve.

01:01.464 --> 01:03.498
You're usually a big old nerd.

01:03.533 --> 01:05.500
Wait! I see
what happened here.

01:05.535 --> 01:08.069
I was one question off
on the Scantron sheet.

01:08.104 --> 01:10.905
See? Here, I-I'll just take it
again real quick and we --

01:10.940 --> 01:14.108
Look, this vape pen isn't gonna
smoke <i> itself </i> behind the gym.

01:14.144 --> 01:15.810
The "F" stands.

01:15.845 --> 01:19.847
F, F, F, F, F, F.
F! F!

01:22.952 --> 01:24.252
Aaaaaaah!

01:24.287 --> 01:25.753
Aaaaaaaaah!

01:25.789 --> 01:28.323
Don't worry.
Barry know what to do.

01:28.358 --> 01:30.224
[ Screaming continues ]

01:33.229 --> 01:34.562
[ Gulps ]

01:34.597 --> 01:39.400
Now...it's just
gonna take me longer...

01:39.436 --> 01:42.537
to finish freaking out.

01:43.473 --> 01:46.274
[ Slow screams ]

01:49.245 --> 01:51.879
♪ Good morning, U.S.A.

01:51.915 --> 01:55.383
♪ I got a feelin' that
it's gonna be a wonderful day ♪

01:55.418 --> 01:58.486
♪ The sun in the sky
has a smile on his face ♪

01:58.521 --> 02:02.957
♪ And he's shinin' a salute
to the American race ♪

02:04.661 --> 02:07.795
♪ Oh, boy, it's swell to say

02:07.831 --> 02:10.298
♪ Good --
♪ Good morning, U.S.A.

02:10.333 --> 02:18.822
<font color="#ec14bd">Sync & corrections by honeybunny
www.addic7ed.com</font>

02:18.942 --> 02:22.076
Buck up, champ. One bad grade's
not the end of the world.

02:22.112 --> 02:23.244
Look at your mother.

02:23.279 --> 02:25.713
She's got a great life,
lives in a nice, big house

02:25.749 --> 02:27.415
and she had nothing but D's.

02:27.450 --> 02:28.416
Yeah.

02:28.451 --> 02:29.684
<i>Double</i> D's.

02:29.719 --> 02:32.220
[ Psychedelic music plays ]

02:37.961 --> 02:40.228
The point is, it was
just one little mistake.

02:40.263 --> 02:41.263
You're gonna be fine.

02:41.297 --> 02:42.830
You know what?
Maybe you're right.

02:42.866 --> 02:44.232
Of course I'm right.

02:44.267 --> 02:46.734
Now, bring that sweet
cinnamon noodle on over here.

02:46.770 --> 02:48.169
It's tousling time.

02:48.204 --> 02:49.737
Come here, you little rascal!
[ Laughs ]

02:49.773 --> 02:51.239
You're a little rascal
is what you are.

02:51.274 --> 02:52.640
Get him! Get that little rascal!
You scamp!

02:52.675 --> 02:54.108
You're just a rascally little scamp!

02:54.144 --> 02:55.777
You little scamp, you.
Oh, he's a scamp is what he is.

02:55.812 --> 02:57.979
Ow!
Now get on out of here, you little bastard.

02:58.014 --> 02:59.614
[ Laughs ]

02:59.649 --> 03:01.182
[ Sighs ]

03:01.217 --> 03:04.652
Our greatest fear has come true.

03:04.687 --> 03:07.155
Candyman has escaped
the world of the movies

03:07.190 --> 03:09.190
and entered ours?!

03:09.225 --> 03:11.626
Okay.<i>My</i> greatest fear
has come true.

03:11.661 --> 03:13.661
Grades are all Steve has.

03:13.696 --> 03:15.696
If he loses that,
what'll he have left?

03:15.732 --> 03:17.632
His dead-on
Paul Hogan impression?

03:17.667 --> 03:19.000
Sure, it kills <i>now,</i>

03:19.035 --> 03:20.635
but how much longer
is that gonna be relevant?

03:20.670 --> 03:22.437
But you said it was no big deal.

03:22.472 --> 03:23.671
I didn't want him to panic.

03:23.706 --> 03:25.807
But what if it wasn't just a mistake?

03:25.842 --> 03:27.775
What if his grades start slipping?

03:27.811 --> 03:28.943
What kind of life will he have?

03:28.978 --> 03:30.645
The world will eat him alive.

03:30.680 --> 03:32.146
Like Candyman?

03:32.182 --> 03:35.116
Yes, Francine, like Candyman.

03:35.952 --> 03:39.053
Steve's always been
a soft, sensitive little guy.

03:39.088 --> 03:41.289
And I've always been there
to protect him.

03:41.324 --> 03:45.092
And now I have to
protect my boy once more --

03:45.128 --> 03:46.260
from failure.

03:46.296 --> 03:49.430
And <i>I</i> need to protect
my girls --

03:49.466 --> 03:50.798
from gravity.

03:50.834 --> 03:53.100
[ Psychedelic music plays ]

03:57.474 --> 03:59.240
[ Screams ]

04:02.773 --> 04:04.473
[ Insects chirping ]

04:05.543 --> 04:07.109
Hey, bud.
Just popping in.

04:07.144 --> 04:08.344
Oh, how's the schoolwork going?

04:08.379 --> 04:09.611
Pretty good.

04:09.647 --> 04:11.180
I'm working on my new
history assignment --

04:11.215 --> 04:13.982
a video presentation
on Charles Lindbergh.

04:14.018 --> 04:16.084
"Bachelor," Season 1.
Sick!

04:16.120 --> 04:19.721
The first aviator to fly nonstop
from New York to Paris?

04:19.757 --> 04:22.357
Oh! Oh,<i>Charles</i> Lindbergh.
Sick!

04:22.393 --> 04:24.126
And Roger's helping me out with it.

04:25.462 --> 04:27.129
Gotcha!

04:27.965 --> 04:31.033
Hey, Rog, can you hit "record"
on the camera?

04:31.068 --> 04:33.268
[ Sighs ]

04:33.304 --> 04:35.003
[ Strains ]

04:38.609 --> 04:40.108
[ Click ]

04:40.144 --> 04:44.313
I, Charles Augustus Lindbergh,
born February 4, 1902,

04:44.348 --> 04:47.249
have just flown my plane,
The Spirit of St. Louis,

04:47.284 --> 04:48.750
across the Atlantic Ocean.

04:48.786 --> 04:51.486
It's a good thing Gene Siskel
was murdered by pirates,

04:51.522 --> 04:53.255
'cause this would've killed him.

04:53.290 --> 04:54.957
I better step in.

04:56.327 --> 04:59.294
Now, look, this is great, son,
but if you really want that "A,"

04:59.330 --> 05:01.363
you're gonna have to go
above and beyond --

05:01.398 --> 05:02.931
really dazzle your teacher.

05:02.967 --> 05:05.067
How do I do that?
Well, I could help you out.

05:05.102 --> 05:07.536
That'd be great!
Roger, do you care if --

05:07.571 --> 05:09.471
I never cared, Steve.

05:09.506 --> 05:13.075
Ah, this is a really hard one.

05:13.110 --> 05:14.142
Yep, nope.

05:16.480 --> 05:18.080
Gotcha!

05:18.115 --> 05:20.515
[ Birds chirping ]

05:20.551 --> 05:24.453
Men's Ed Hardy "Death or Glory"
low-rise sneakers.

05:24.488 --> 05:27.189
Color -- dragon smoke black.

05:27.224 --> 05:29.625
Size -- 14.

05:29.660 --> 05:31.693
Now, all I need...

05:31.729 --> 05:33.528
is a body.

05:33.564 --> 05:37.266
[ Somber piano music plays ]

05:37.301 --> 05:41.103
♪ These shiny shoes
will cure my blues ♪

05:41.138 --> 05:44.940
♪ Und chase the gloom away

05:44.975 --> 05:48.443
♪ When I dress my body

05:48.479 --> 05:52.881
♪ The one I'll have someday

05:52.916 --> 05:56.151
♪ "Co-Ed naked volleyball"

05:56.186 --> 05:59.821
♪ Is what my shirt will say

05:59.857 --> 06:03.258
♪ Und puka shells
will sure look swell ♪

06:03.294 --> 06:08.063
♪ Paired with
a white gold chain ♪

06:08.098 --> 06:10.966
♪ I'll have no fear,
only joy and cheer ♪

06:11.001 --> 06:17.806
♪ And a square-cut stud
in my left ear ♪

06:17.841 --> 06:20.442
♪ When I dress my body,
I'll hear everybody say ♪

06:20.477 --> 06:23.712
♪ "Hey, that's somebody,
not just anybody" ♪

06:23.747 --> 06:29.918
♪ When I dress my body

06:29.953 --> 06:33.922
♪ Someday --

06:33.957 --> 06:35.724
Klaus!
What the hell?!

06:35.759 --> 06:36.958
I'm doing a thing in here!

06:36.994 --> 06:38.593
It's <i>my</i> room!
W-Why are you even --

06:38.629 --> 06:39.494
Get out!

06:39.530 --> 06:40.696
<i>My</i> room, Klaus!

06:40.731 --> 06:42.130
Out!
Aaaaah!

06:42.166 --> 06:43.198
Fine!

06:44.401 --> 06:46.234
[ Door slams ]

06:46.270 --> 06:54.343
♪ Someday

06:56.213 --> 06:58.914
What better way
to go above and beyond

06:58.949 --> 07:01.616
than to get some sweet
aerial footage for your movie?

07:01.652 --> 07:04.186
So I borrowed a drone from work.

07:04.221 --> 07:05.854
Dad, that's a <i>Predator</i> drone!

07:05.889 --> 07:07.296
Eh, a drone's a drone.

07:07.416 --> 07:09.406
I just got in there with my leather man,
yanked out the middleman,

07:09.526 --> 07:11.393
tossed them in the "everything"
drawer in the kitchen.

07:11.428 --> 07:12.794
No big whoop.

07:12.796 --> 07:16.131
Now, where's that car wash coupon?

07:17.334 --> 07:18.834
Let's start with the scene
where I find out

07:18.869 --> 07:20.235
my baby's been kidnapped
and --

07:20.270 --> 07:22.971
Actually, I made
one other super-cool change

07:23.006 --> 07:24.806
I know you're gonna love.

07:24.842 --> 07:27.976
Steve, meet the new star
of your history project --

07:28.011 --> 07:31.113
The Rock...'s
friend Vin Diesel --

07:31.148 --> 07:32.714
still, technically, a star.

07:32.750 --> 07:35.217
Uh, we're not actually friends.

07:35.252 --> 07:38.720
Although, we do own a couple
Long John Silver's together.

07:38.756 --> 07:40.422
But that's not important.

07:40.457 --> 07:44.626
What's important is,

07:44.661 --> 07:47.229
and I'm gonna make it come true.

07:47.264 --> 07:49.104
You told him I'm
a Make-A-Wish kid, didn't you?

07:49.133 --> 07:51.099
Am I that far off, Steve?

07:53.886 --> 07:55.286
What are we doing
at the C.I.A.?

07:55.321 --> 07:57.755
Oh, just taking advantage of our...

07:57.790 --> 07:59.223
top-secret soundstage!

07:59.259 --> 08:00.992
[ Indistinct conversations ]

08:01.027 --> 08:02.827
This is where we filmed
the moon landing,

08:02.862 --> 08:04.095
the JFK assassination,

08:04.130 --> 08:06.163
and Def Jam's
"How to be a Player."

08:06.199 --> 08:09.700
Wow! This is gonna be the most
epic history project ever!

08:09.736 --> 08:11.235
You bet your ass it is.

08:11.271 --> 08:13.838
Now, wait here. I'm gonna go
check on the script changes.

08:13.873 --> 08:15.406
Script changes?
What are --

08:15.441 --> 08:16.540
Apple box flyin' in!

08:16.576 --> 08:18.242
Dino, let's put sticks
on a half apple

08:18.278 --> 08:20.444
and fly in a couple of C-47s
so I can jelly-roll

08:20.480 --> 08:22.847
those Bob Denvers,
and put 'em on an apple box.

08:22.882 --> 08:24.915
Hey!
You can't touch that!

08:24.951 --> 08:26.717
[ Sighs ]
And you are?

08:26.753 --> 08:28.986
Chuck Deptula, union gaffer,

08:29.022 --> 08:30.521
but everybody calls me
"Cheese."

08:30.556 --> 08:31.989
You seem to be a lot more helpful <i>now</i>

08:32.025 --> 08:33.591
than you were the other day.

08:33.626 --> 08:36.360
<i>Now</i> the International
Brotherhood of Film Grips,

08:36.395 --> 08:40.597
Session Drummers and Pool Table
Repairmen has my back, scab.

08:40.633 --> 08:42.133
That's lunch!

08:43.535 --> 08:47.505
Hmm. This still doesn't feel
like a guaranteed "A."

08:47.540 --> 08:49.440
Atlantic Ocean?
Pacific's bigger.

08:49.475 --> 08:51.375
Steve's teacher will find that
much more impressive.

08:51.411 --> 08:53.051
I think maybe he'll care
a little bit more

08:53.079 --> 08:54.645
about historical accuracy.

08:54.681 --> 08:57.548
Uh, If <i>I</i> didn't care
about historical accuracy,

08:57.583 --> 08:59.984
would I have stolen
the actual Spirit of St. Louis

09:00.019 --> 09:02.086
from the Smithsonian?
What?!

09:02.121 --> 09:04.889
The toughest part was convincing
the guard I came in with it.

09:04.924 --> 09:06.657
Look, to really impress your teacher,

09:06.693 --> 09:10.227
we gotta make this thing
big, exciting, fun.

09:10.263 --> 09:12.196
Wait --
the Lindbergh baby died?!

09:12.231 --> 09:14.231
Huge downer, Steve.
Yeah, but --

09:14.267 --> 09:16.767
What if Lindbergh had a buddy,
like a-a dog or a monkey,

09:16.803 --> 09:18.302
and the buddy dies instead?

09:18.338 --> 09:20.237
I'm not sure --
You know what? Now I like the buddy.

09:20.273 --> 09:23.007
Maybe Lindbergh
brings him back to life

09:23.042 --> 09:25.209
with the power of RC Cola!

09:25.244 --> 09:27.378
We gotta work in some product
placement to cover costs.

09:27.413 --> 09:29.780
Dad! This is
<i>my</i> project, remember?

09:29.816 --> 09:32.650
Hey, you're still in charge.
We're just here to help <i>you.</i>

09:32.685 --> 09:35.553
"We," being DreamSmith Entertainment,

09:35.588 --> 09:37.054
the production company I started

09:37.090 --> 09:38.756
with the money
from your college fund.

09:38.791 --> 09:40.191
I'll tell you
one thing, Suit --

09:40.226 --> 09:42.960
we've got non-union sound,
so the movie's gonna

09:42.995 --> 09:44.462
[ Feedback ]
sound like shit!

09:44.497 --> 09:45.730
Owww!

09:45.765 --> 09:46.831
Oooh!

09:46.866 --> 09:48.165
That's lunch!

09:50.603 --> 09:51.603
Refresh.

09:51.637 --> 09:52.603
Refresh.

09:52.638 --> 09:53.604
Refresh.

09:53.639 --> 09:54.739
[ Gasps ]

09:54.774 --> 09:56.340
Hayley!
The shoes are here!

09:56.376 --> 09:58.476
The shoes, the shoes,
the shoes, the shoes!

10:00.646 --> 10:02.947
But...it said...

10:02.982 --> 10:04.548
[ Voice breaking ]
H-How?

10:04.584 --> 10:05.816
[ Crying ]

10:05.852 --> 10:08.919
You know, there is
a 416 <i>South</i> Cherry Street.

10:08.955 --> 10:10.755
Maybe it got delivered there
by mistake.

10:10.790 --> 10:13.791
As a matter of fact, I once
ordered a Garfield welcome mat

10:13.826 --> 10:15.259
that never showed up, either.

10:15.294 --> 10:19.263
Oh, I do <i>so</i> hope
to someday hear the story

10:19.298 --> 10:21.432
of the missing welcome mat.

10:21.467 --> 10:22.867
Hey, I'm trying to help you out.

10:22.902 --> 10:24.468
Then shut up and drive!

10:26.939 --> 10:28.906
We shut down the set of "Captain Ron"

10:28.941 --> 10:31.208
for six months back in '91.

10:31.244 --> 10:33.644
Touchstone retaliated with full fury.

10:33.679 --> 10:36.580
Friendships were destroyed,
marriages fell apart,

10:36.616 --> 10:40.151
but, by God, we got three chairs
for every five men working.

10:40.186 --> 10:41.852
Dino, you'd be standing right now.

10:41.888 --> 10:44.622
Um, Cheese, we're trying
to film a scene.

10:44.657 --> 10:46.891
Well,<i>we're</i> trying to eat lunch,

10:46.926 --> 10:49.093
which we're allowed to do
anywhere on set.

10:49.128 --> 10:50.928
Read the '85 agreement!

10:50.963 --> 10:51.929
That's lunch!

10:51.964 --> 10:53.297
Come on, Dino.

10:56.169 --> 10:58.569
Hey, man, this is for a sick kid.

10:58.604 --> 11:00.404
Couldn't you be a little flexible?

11:00.440 --> 11:02.306
Oh, so you think
you can crap all over us

11:02.341 --> 11:04.508
below-the-line people just
because you're the big star?

11:04.544 --> 11:05.810
How dare you!

11:05.845 --> 11:08.712
I'm gonna eat lunch
in your trailer, in your bed!

11:08.748 --> 11:09.947
Please join me!

11:09.982 --> 11:12.116
I know I sound angry,
but please come!

11:12.151 --> 11:13.818
My God, you're ripped.

11:13.853 --> 11:15.586
Okay, everybody, back to 1.

11:15.621 --> 11:16.720
And...

11:16.756 --> 11:18.789
Are you worried this scene
is playing too heavy?

11:18.825 --> 11:20.391
No, I'm not.
And...

11:20.426 --> 11:22.126
You sure you don't want
to bring in the monkey?

11:22.161 --> 11:23.494
Yes, positive!

11:23.529 --> 11:25.296
And...action!

11:25.331 --> 11:27.531
You fly the plane
or the plane --

11:27.567 --> 11:28.766
Cut!

11:28.801 --> 11:31.068
Let's just bring the monkey in,
see what he does.

11:31.103 --> 11:32.336
Dad! That's enough!

11:32.371 --> 11:34.638
is is <i>my</i> project!
Oh, really?

11:34.674 --> 11:36.373
Because it sure feels like
<i>I'm</i> the one

11:36.409 --> 11:38.108
who's been putting in all the effort.

11:38.144 --> 11:40.778
I got you the soundstage,
I got you Vin Diesel,

11:40.813 --> 11:42.213
I got you a monkey

11:42.248 --> 11:44.348
who studied under the monkey
from "Dunston Checks In"!

11:44.383 --> 11:46.450
I didn't ask you to!!

11:46.486 --> 11:49.053
But you <i>need</i> me to,
if you want to get that "A."

11:49.088 --> 11:51.489
I'm sorry, son, but you're
no Charles Lindbergh.

11:51.524 --> 11:54.492
You can't fly solo on this.
You're just not capable.

11:58.464 --> 12:01.265
Nope, sorry. I haven't gotten
any packages lately.

12:01.300 --> 12:03.033
Oh, well.
It was a long shot.

12:03.069 --> 12:04.368
Take 'er easy.

12:04.403 --> 12:06.637
Hey, I'll take 'er
any way I can get 'er.

12:06.672 --> 12:09.540
[ Both laugh ]

12:09.575 --> 12:10.541
[ Chuckles ]

12:10.576 --> 12:13.944
That lying son of a bitch
has my shoes.

12:13.980 --> 12:15.513
Klaus, that's ridiculous.

12:15.548 --> 12:17.615
Okay, we have no reason
to --

12:17.650 --> 12:19.550
Son of a bitch!

12:22.822 --> 12:24.088
What the --

12:24.123 --> 12:26.857
Oh, you want to get nuts?
Let's get nuts!

12:26.893 --> 12:30.394
I brought so many bullets!

12:30.429 --> 12:33.664
[ Cheers and applause ]

12:33.699 --> 12:37.468
Ladies, gentlemen,
Steve's teacher, welcome.

12:37.503 --> 12:40.337
You're not gonna believe
your eyes when you see

12:40.373 --> 12:44.275
what Steve Smith was capable
of doing all by himself.

12:45.545 --> 12:47.378
Roll it!

12:52.885 --> 12:54.818
[ Roars ]

13:01.294 --> 13:02.860
[ Screeches ]

13:04.597 --> 13:07.731
Child:
[ Whispering ] DreamSmith.

13:12.705 --> 13:15.205
Father Lindbergh:
<i>Your head's in the clouds, boy.</i>

13:15.241 --> 13:16.740
<i>That's no place for a man.</i>

13:16.776 --> 13:19.376
Lindbergh:
<i>But what if it was, Pop?</i>

13:19.412 --> 13:21.845
<i>What if it was?</i>

13:21.881 --> 13:27.351
<i>I shall call my invention
"the aeroplane,"</i>

13:27.386 --> 13:31.021
<i>and I owe it all to RC Cola.</i>

13:31.057 --> 13:32.089
[ <i>Tab pops</i> ]

13:32.124 --> 13:33.624
[ <i>Gulping</i> ]

13:33.659 --> 13:36.293
Lindbergh's wife: <i>Charles!
Our baby's been kidnapped!</i>

13:36.329 --> 13:38.028
<i>I'll handle this.</i>

13:38.064 --> 13:39.229
[ <i>Tab pops</i> ]

13:39.265 --> 13:41.198
[ <i>Gulping</i> ]

13:45.304 --> 13:47.171
Hey, Boss, ain't you worried

13:47.206 --> 13:49.373
Lindbergh will come for his bambino?

13:49.408 --> 13:51.909
He is just one man.

13:51.944 --> 13:54.578
[ Dramatic music plays ]

13:54.614 --> 13:59.016
One pilot with two <i>fight</i> attendants.

13:59.051 --> 14:00.851
[ Smooches ]

14:02.154 --> 14:03.454
[ Glass shatters ]

14:06.926 --> 14:08.392
Aaaaaaaah!

14:09.195 --> 14:10.461
Guards!

14:11.263 --> 14:12.529
[ Whistles ]

14:20.806 --> 14:21.772
Aaaaaaaa--

14:21.807 --> 14:22.873
Ugh!

14:24.176 --> 14:27.277
You got a bad <i>altitude.</i>

14:28.114 --> 14:29.780
Good work, Gus.

14:29.815 --> 14:32.549
But next time, <i>you</i> fly.

14:32.585 --> 14:35.386
♪ I just want to fly

14:35.421 --> 14:36.987
[ Applause ]

14:37.023 --> 14:40.190
♪ Put your arms
around me, baby... ♪

14:40.226 --> 14:42.326
And now let's meet the genius behind

14:42.361 --> 14:46.230
this A-plus-caliber project --
Steve Smith.

14:46.265 --> 14:48.666
[ Audience murmuring ]

14:48.701 --> 14:50.300
What?!

14:50.336 --> 14:52.836
[ Gasps ] De plane!

14:56.342 --> 14:58.342
Can't do things on my own, can I?

14:58.377 --> 15:01.779
Well, look who's flying solo
now, Dad!

15:02.648 --> 15:04.381
At least <i>Mom's</i> still proud of me.

15:04.417 --> 15:07.084
[ Thunder crashes ]
[ Whimpers ]

15:07.119 --> 15:08.452
[ Knocking ]

15:08.487 --> 15:09.887
Candyman's got me!

15:09.922 --> 15:13.791
You gotta say my name
three times to free me!

15:13.826 --> 15:15.459
[ Screams ]

15:19.273 --> 15:22.441
Now, just because you have
no idea how to fly a plane,

15:22.476 --> 15:23.809
there's no need to panic.

15:23.844 --> 15:25.644
You can make it to Paris.

15:25.680 --> 15:27.513
You'll just have to learn on the fly.

15:27.548 --> 15:29.114
[ Giggles ]
Good one, Steve.

15:29.150 --> 15:32.051
You've been cleared to laugh.
[ Laughs ]

15:32.086 --> 15:35.688
Well, I should probably figure
out what all these gauges are.

15:35.723 --> 15:36.889
Air speed.

15:36.924 --> 15:40.159
I'd say that one's
self-explanatory.

15:40.194 --> 15:41.226
This one...

15:42.730 --> 15:44.363
Gonna come back to this one.

15:44.398 --> 15:48.000
It's so foggy up here.
I hope I'm flying high enough.

15:49.303 --> 15:50.303
[ Water splashes ]

15:50.338 --> 15:52.438
[ Dolphins chatter ]

15:54.642 --> 15:55.708
Aaaaah!

15:55.743 --> 15:58.744
Geez, buddy!
Got enough arms?!

16:01.382 --> 16:03.048
Pull up! Pull up!

16:08.022 --> 16:11.623
Looks like white men <i>can</i> jump.

16:11.659 --> 16:14.026
[ Wind whistling ]

16:15.796 --> 16:17.229
[ Thud ]

16:17.264 --> 16:19.932
[ Gasps ]
Looks like white men <i>can</i> jump.

16:19.967 --> 16:22.668
What?
It's a famous novel, Steve.

16:22.703 --> 16:23.736
Now, give me that flight stick.

16:23.771 --> 16:24.737
Never!

16:24.772 --> 16:26.305
[ Both grunting ]

16:29.944 --> 16:32.211
[ Glass shattering ]

16:32.246 --> 16:33.012
[ Grunts ]

16:33.047 --> 16:34.813
Douglas, Douglas, Douglas.

16:34.849 --> 16:37.683
All I want are my shoes.

16:37.718 --> 16:39.952
I don't have your shoes.

16:39.987 --> 16:43.322
Please, you -- you can have
<i>my</i> shoes. Here.

16:43.357 --> 16:45.991
Do I look like the kind of fish
who would wear red shoes

16:46.027 --> 16:47.726
when he someday has
the body of a man?!

16:47.762 --> 16:50.963
House is clean. Only place
I haven't looked is this closet.

16:50.998 --> 16:52.598
Thing's locked tight.

16:52.633 --> 16:54.867
Open the closet, please, Doug.

16:54.902 --> 16:56.335
I-I lost the key.
Listen --

16:56.370 --> 16:58.504
Open the closet!
I didn't take your stuff!

16:58.539 --> 17:01.407
Then why is my Garfield mat
on your doorstep?!

17:01.442 --> 17:04.576
It's Garfield! It's Amazon's
top-selling welcome mat!

17:04.612 --> 17:06.545
Open the closet, Doug!
I can't! I swear to you!

17:06.579 --> 17:08.646
I don't have the key! Please!
Open it, or I swear I'll shoot!

17:08.682 --> 17:10.782
[ All screaming ]

17:10.818 --> 17:13.152
[ Teakettle whistles ]
[ Screams ]

17:20.728 --> 17:24.163
Oh...my...God!

17:24.198 --> 17:26.498
There are no shoes in there.

17:26.534 --> 17:30.669
We've inconvenienced
an innocent man and his guest.

17:30.704 --> 17:32.404
[ Muffled begging ]

17:32.440 --> 17:35.340
You know, I'm not 100% sure
I ordered that welcome mat.

17:35.376 --> 17:37.009
I might've just put it
on my wish list.

17:37.044 --> 17:38.410
[ Cellphone bloops ]

17:38.446 --> 17:40.712
It's Jeff. He found your shoes
in the bush out front.

17:40.748 --> 17:44.316
The bush! Of course!

17:44.351 --> 17:46.952
[ Whistling ]

17:46.987 --> 17:48.854
[ Door opens, closes ]

17:51.759 --> 17:52.991
[ Whistling ]

17:57.298 --> 18:00.999
Steve: Let go!
<i>I'm</i> doing this -- on my own!

18:01.035 --> 18:04.269
Why...won't you...
just let me help you?!

18:04.305 --> 18:06.338
Because you're <i>not</i> helping me!

18:06.373 --> 18:09.875
When you...won't let me do
anything for myself,

18:09.910 --> 18:12.444
you're actually standing in my way!

18:13.247 --> 18:15.247
I am?
Yes! That's the --

18:15.282 --> 18:17.416
Shh! I'm remembering
something.

18:17.451 --> 18:20.986
A lesson, from a powerful film
I once saw.

18:22.156 --> 18:24.123
[ Voice breaking ]
Don't leave me, Pop!

18:24.158 --> 18:26.992
I can't do this
without you by my side.

18:27.027 --> 18:29.461
Oh, stop your foolishness, now.

18:29.497 --> 18:35.067
Why, if you never let
a baby bird out of the nest,

18:35.102 --> 18:37.803
it can't never take flight.

18:37.838 --> 18:39.104
[ Groans ]

18:39.140 --> 18:42.774
Take flight,
Charles...Lindbergh...

18:42.810 --> 18:43.775
my son.

18:43.811 --> 18:45.043
[ Flatline ]

18:45.079 --> 18:47.112
[ Sobbing ]

18:52.720 --> 18:54.153
Don't you see, Dad?

18:54.188 --> 18:57.256
If you never let me try,
sure, I can't ever fail.

18:57.291 --> 19:00.926
But you can't ever succeed, either.

19:00.961 --> 19:02.694
Oh, I'm sorry, son.

19:02.730 --> 19:04.396
Well, I'm sorry, too.

19:04.431 --> 19:06.665
It was pretty stupid of me
taking off with this plane

19:06.700 --> 19:10.169
and thinking I could make it
across the ocean all by myself.

19:13.374 --> 19:15.641
Oh, my God!
The Eiffel Tower!

19:15.676 --> 19:17.276
I did make it to Paris!

19:17.311 --> 19:19.611
[ As Paul Hogan ]
Wanna bring us in for a landing, mate?

19:19.647 --> 19:21.346
Heh! Still got it!

19:21.382 --> 19:23.348
But, actually, son, I realize now

19:23.384 --> 19:26.852
that this is something I have to
let you do on your own.

19:26.887 --> 19:28.153
What?!

19:28.189 --> 19:30.756
No, wait! I don't know
how to land a plane!

19:30.791 --> 19:33.325
White men <i>can</i> jump.

19:35.663 --> 19:37.196
[ Groans ]

19:37.231 --> 19:41.233
I believe in yoooooooou!

19:43.737 --> 19:45.637
Merci!

19:45.673 --> 19:47.005
[ Thud ]

19:47.041 --> 19:48.540
[ Wind whistles ]

19:52.880 --> 19:54.746
All right, son, you can do this.

19:54.782 --> 19:56.949
Just mind those crosswinds.

19:56.984 --> 19:58.984
Good, good.
Easy on the throttle.

19:59.019 --> 20:00.719
Pull back on the yoke.

20:00.754 --> 20:02.921
That's it, now.
Steady.

20:02.957 --> 20:04.056
Steady.

20:05.025 --> 20:06.258
[ Gasps ]

20:08.896 --> 20:11.430
My boy!
What have I done?!

20:11.465 --> 20:13.599
[ Sobbing ]

20:15.202 --> 20:16.602
Ow! My bottom!

20:16.637 --> 20:18.303
Steve! You're alive!

20:18.339 --> 20:21.273
Can you believe I actually
made it all the way to Paris?!

20:21.308 --> 20:23.609
Well...no,
because you didn't.

20:23.644 --> 20:25.844
Looks like you must've gotten
turned around in the clouds,

20:25.879 --> 20:28.013
'cause that's that new
amusement park they opened

20:28.048 --> 20:30.015
just outside Langley Falls.

20:33.087 --> 20:34.620
Tell you what, son.

20:34.655 --> 20:37.456
From now on, I'm gonna let you
do things for yourself.

20:37.491 --> 20:40.926
But if you ever do want my help,
all you have to do is ask.

20:40.961 --> 20:42.861
Maybe you can help me
wash my flight suit.

20:42.896 --> 20:46.031
I really did a number on this
thing baling out of that plane.

20:46.066 --> 20:47.399
A number 5.

20:47.434 --> 20:49.468
That's two number 2s and a number 1.

20:49.503 --> 20:53.338
That sounds like the kind
of help a <i>mother</i> might give.

20:54.823 --> 21:00.181
